<p style=3D"color:#333"><small>By Trudi Roth</small></p>

<p style=3D"color:#333">For most of us, the pandemic is a source of additio=
nal financial stress. I say =E2=80=9Cadditional=E2=80=9D because Gen X is u=
sed to being known as savings slackers, maybe due to our unique position of=
 supporting both growing children and aging parents. That means worries abo=
ut our family=E2=80=99s physical health are compounded by financial health =
concerns.</p>

<p style=3D"color:#333">Then again, the Great Pause has also put the brakes=
 on normal spending patterns. We=E2=80=99re more focused on what=E2=80=99s =
essential, and less able or interested in shopping for fun and sport.</p>

<p style=3D"color:#333">This naturally compels us to become more aware of o=
ur finances =E2=80=94 which makes it the perfect time to harness the power =
of a Japanese technique for mindful budgeting: kakeibo.</p>

<h4 style=3D"font-family:calluna,Georgia,serif;color:#111;font-size:22px;ma=
rgin-bottom:0px;margin-top:30px">Kondo your financial house</h4>

<p style=3D"color:#333">Kakeibo (or kakebo) was created by Japanese journal=
ist Hani Motoko in 1904 as a household accounting system, and it blends tho=
ughtful goal-setting with bookkeeping. The <a href=3D"https://t.dripemail2.=
com/c/eyJhY2NvdW50X2lkIjoiNDMxMTg3MCIsImRlbGl2ZXJ5X2lkIjoidzRoZTlvMWQzMjM2Z=
